on and biopolitics, Steinlight brings the crowds that pervade nineteenth-century fiction into the foreground. In so doing, she transforms the subject and political stakes of the Victorian novel, dislodging the longstanding idea that its central category is the individual by demonstrating how fiction is altered by its emerging concern with population. By overpopulating narrative space and imagining the human species perpetually in excess of the existing social order, she shows, fiction made it necessary to radically reimagine life in the aggregate.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEnglish fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFertility, Human, in literature. 0aMalthusianism. 0aPopulation in literature. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aWest European History. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  apopulation in nineteenth century literature, Victorian biopolitics, Victorian fiction and the masses, the nineteenth century British novel and demography, Malthus and literature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060655308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2018 Englishz978311060418408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2018z9783110603187oZDB-23-DKU40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150171072840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501710728423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501710728/original  a978-3-11-060418-4  E